               <forename type="first">William</forename>
               <surname>Allen</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1770"/>
            <death when="1843"/>
            <note>Allen was a Quaker who worked in the pharmaceutical industry. Davy asked him to give lectures on natural philosophy at the RI. FRSL.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_368">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Horace Bénédict de</forename>
               <surname>Saussure</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1740"/>
            <death when="1799"/>
            <note>Genevan geologist, meteorologist, physicist, mountaineer and Alpine expolorer. Often referred to as the founder of Alpinism and modern meteorology.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_066">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">John</forename>
               <surname>Dalton</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1766"/>
            <death when="1844"/>
            <note>Mancunian chemist and natural philosopher who lectured at the Royal Institution. He formulated a version of the atomic theory of matter much disliked by Davy. FRSL.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_030">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Antoine-Laurent</forename>
               <surname>Lavoisier</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1742"/>
            <death when="1794"/>
            <note>French chemist and tax farmer (for which he was guillotined). Developed a new nomenclature for chemistry (much of which is still in use today) and argued strongly against the existence of phlogiston. Davy read some of his writings while in Cornwall which he then opposed and throughout his career maintained an ambivalent attitude towards Lavoisierian chemisty. ForMemRSL.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_016">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Joseph</forename>
               <surname>Priestley</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1733"/>
            <death when="1804"/>
            <note>Unitarian and political radical forced into exile in Pennsylvania. As a natural philospher and chemist who retained belief in phlogiston, he discovered oxygen and nitrous oxide though not under those names. FRSL.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_331">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Christoph Heinrich</forename>
               <surname>Pfaff</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1773"/>
            <death when="1852"/>
            <note>German physician, chemist and physicist who worked on animal electricity alongside Volta and Humboldt. The younger brother of mathematician Johann Friedrich Pfaff.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_199">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Alessandro</forename>
               <surname>Volta</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1745"/>
            <death when="1827"/>
            <note>Professor of experimental physics at the University of Pavia. At the end of the eighteenth century he Invented the Voltaic pile which produced electric current and which Davy shortly dubbed the battery. Davy described meeting him in 1814 in notebook 14/I, p.38. ForMemRSL.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_603">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Antonio de</forename>
               <surname>Marti Franques</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1750"/>
            <death when="1832"/>
            <note>Catalan chemist who also worked in geology and mereorology amongst other disciplines.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_005">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Claude Louis</forename>
               <surname>Berthollet</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1748"/>
            <death when="1822"/>
            <note>French Chemist. ForMemRSL.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_163">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Thomas Charles</forename>
               <surname>Hope</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1766"/>
            <death when="1844"/>
            <note>Professor of Medicine and Chemistry at Edinburgh University. Discovered the element strontium and seems to have played a role in Davy's appointment to the Royal Institution. FRSL.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_271">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Alexander von</forename>
               <surname>Humboldt</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1769"/>
            <death when="1859"/>
            <note>German geographer, naturalist and explorer. ForMemRSL.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_617">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Carlo Lodovico</forename>
               <surname>Morozzo</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1743"/>
            <death when="1804"/>
            <note>Morozzo was an Italian chemist.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_226">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Thomas</forename>
               <surname>Thomson</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1773"/>
            <death when="1852"/>
            <note>Scottish chemist and mineralogist whose writings contributed to the early spread of Dalton's atomic theory. FRSL.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_616">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Théodore Turquet de</forename>
               <surname>Mayerne</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1573"/>
            <death when="1655"/>
            <note>Genevean born physician who worked in France and England, where he was royal physician for which he was knighted.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_021">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Stephen</forename>
               <surname>Hales</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1677"/>
            <death when="1761"/>
            <note>English clergyman who made major contributions to a range of scientific fields including botany, pneumatic chemistry and physiology.  FRSL.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_026">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Henry</forename>
               <surname>Cavendish</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1731"/>
            <death when="1810"/>
            <note>A central figure in English natural philosophy and chemistry, among other research he determined the density of the earth and discovered what would later be named hydrogen. He was one of the people who helped appoint Davy to the Royal Institution. Following his death in 1810 Davy delivered a widely-quoted eulogy on Cavendish and later arranged for some of his apparatus to be transferred to the Royal Institution. FRSL. </note>
         </person>
